    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That sounds like a good start for the students. Some people I've talked to argue that this kind of broad interpretation is actually a problem though—that it lets judges basically make up new rights instead of just following what's written in the Constitution. How would you explain that critique to my class so they understand why it's such a controversial thing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics of substantive due process argue that it grants judges too much power to rewrite the Constitution based on their own personal values rather than the text or history of the Founding Fathers. This \"judicial activism\" approach often leads to the erosion of democratic self-governance, as unelected justices decide major social issues without public debate or legislative input. For example, the overturning of *Roe v. Wade* and the *Dobbs* decision highlighted how deeply controversial and divisive this expansive interpretation can become when it conflicts with the will of the people. Therefore, while proponents see it as necessary protection for minorities, opponents view it as an overreach that undermines the rule of law and the separation of powers.",
      "source": "target",
